<p><code>br</code> makes a break <code>p</code> makes a paragraph
<br>you can use <code>br</code> within other elements
<br>you can use <code>br</code> multiple times to add more space</p>

<br>
<br>

<p>html tags start and end the entire document
<br><code>br</code> is an empty element
<br>elements can be nested
<br>this creates a new line without a space, unlike <code>p</code>
<br>use lowercase and quotes for attributes
<br>you can use "" and '' to show double quotes withing title attributes</p>

<p>This is an example of code: <code>I can't figure out how to use tags within code elements </code> </p>

<p><code>a</code>: attributes, such a size, width, height, etc.
<br>href, hypertext reference
<br>img, image
<br>src, source
<br>
<br>
<a href="https://hannahdiazart.com/">Add text after link before closing the attribute tag to create a text link</a>
<img src="https://aaforringer.files.wordpress.com/2014/09/bear-table.jpg">
<img src="https://i.imgflip.com/109y7u.jpg" width="300" alt="Bear at table">
<br>You can input width="" and height="" manually, or it will scale to whichever dimension you choose
<br>You can input alt="" to write a description of the photo if the image no longer exists</p>

<p title="I'm a paragraph on style" style="color:red">I am a new paragraph
<br>there are many, many more style options to add to this tag</p>
<! add title attributes in paragraphs>

<p title="This section is about headings">Headings range from sizes 1 (largest) to 6 (smallest)
<br>these are what search engines use to index your pages
<br>or you can use the <code>font-size</code> property to specify
<br>such as:

<h1 style="font-size:60px;">This is 60px</h1>

this is not for making font bold or bigger, it's just for headings
<br>
<h1>This is heading 1</h1>
